{"ts": "2026-06-09T17:52:17.750848+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "I now have a complete picture. Here is my triage:\n\n---\n\n## Triage Summary for Issue #1\n\n**Issue:** `gif` profile output looks washed out / banded compared to gifski or a manual two-pass palettegen/paletteuse pipeline.\n\n### Evidence\n\n1. **`profiles.toml` (line ~28–31)** already documents this as a **known limitation**:\n   > *\"the gif profile currently uses a single-pass palette generation, which is convenient but produces noticeably worse quality than a proper two-pass palettegen / paletteuse pipeline. Known limitation; tracked in the issue tracker.\"*\n\n2. **`src/vidpack/runner.py` (lines 15–19)** confirms the gif branch applies only `fps` and `scale` filters with **no `palettegen`/`paletteuse` step** — meaning ffmpeg uses its default fixed 256-color table, which produces banding on gradients and saturated colors.\n\n3. The **README** describes the gif profile's video codec as `(palette)`, which is slightly misleading given that no palette optimization is actually performed.\n\n### Verdict\n\nThis is a **valid, already-documented known limitation** — not a new bug. The issue accurately diagnoses the root cause (single-pass without palette generation) and the reproduction steps are clear and correct.\n\n### Recommended Action\n\nThe appropriate action is to **add a comment** acknowledging the issue, noting that this is a known limitation already tracked/documented in the codebase, and keeping it open as an **enhancement request** for future two-pass gif support.\n\nHowever, all write operations (comment, label, update) are failing with **403 permission errors** — the provided token does not have write access to this repository. I am unable to post the comment, add a label, or close the issue programmatically.\n\n**Intended comment** (if permissions allowed):\n\n> Thanks for the clear report! This is a known limitation already documented in `profiles.toml` and `runner.py`. The gif profile currently uses a single-pass approach with no `palettegen`/`paletteuse` filter, which causes the banding you're seeing. A two-pass pipeline would definitely improve quality. Keeping this open as an enhancement request — contributions welcome if anyone wants to tackle the two-pass implementation.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 859, "prompt_tokens": 11936, "total_tokens": 12795, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 379, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 11520}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "mimo-v2.5-pro", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "26cd7cc3ca3b45f5a51a22f2d0425fe3", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ead83-1b5d-79c0-9f63-dd9ac5482eb2-0", "tool_calls": [], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11936, "output_tokens": 859, "total_tokens": 12795, "input_token_details": {"cache_read": 11520}, "output_token_details": {"reasoning": 379}}}}]}}}
